This process may include the use of questionnaires, surveys, and observations of how the individual responds to auditory stimuli (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Currently, there is no single diagnostic tool or test with a high success rate, nor is there a known cause for CAPD. Diagnostic tests often involve presenting the individual with multiple auditory stimuli simultaneously, requiring them to distinguish between specific elements, such as words or numbers. More advanced assessments might involve measuring acoustic signals within the ear and observing the responses to these signals.

My educational journey in social work is driven by a desire to build a career with the Division of Family and Children Services, where my goal is to support children who have experienced abuse or neglect and to assist families in distress. I bring to the field values such as service, respect, ethics, and a dedication to fostering better relationships while continuously improving my professional abilities to stay effective in my work. These principles are not only fundamental to social work but are also deeply significant to me on a personal level.

Helping others has always been my aspiration, though I initially struggled to identify the exact career path I wanted. During high school and college, I observed many people who avoided confronting their challenges, and some adopted poor coping strategies. These observations motivated me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still uncertain about my career direction after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I took some time off. That summer, I happened to visit a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy on her couch. He was there seeking refuge from his abusive parents. The following day, I learned he had involved the police at his parents' home. Wanting to help, I went over to his parents' house to express my concerns privately to the officers, mentioning my recent Psychology degree. The police asked me to speak with the parents, as legally they couldn't intervene for the teenager. When I spoke to the parents, they were uneasy and offered excuses for their son’s behavior, labeling his actions as “manipulative” for involving others in “simple” family matters. This incident propelled me to seriously contemplate a career in social work to aid children facing such “simple” familial conflicts.

Social justice is another cornerstone of social work that holds significant importance for me. Society often emphasizes the value of the individual and mourns those we lose, yet the societal idea of the “individual” often follows outdated norms rather than true uniqueness. If society mourns individuals, why do we strive for uniformity? I cherish my individuality and resist conforming to others' standards. Throughout my time in high school and college, I consistently opposed social injustice through personal expression like unconventional hair and clothing, multiple ear piercings, active participation in the GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and standing against racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. I am committed to the cause of social justice and will persist in challenging social inequities.

This essay explores both the Biological and Sociocultural frameworks as they pertain to insomnia. The Biological perspective emphasizes inherited genetic traits and medical components of health. In contrast, the Sociocultural perspective examines environmental interactions and their relevance to factors like race, ethnicity, demographic information, and socioeconomic status. This analysis of insomnia evaluates these models and delves into selected research to elucidate and enhance understanding of these frameworks. The research explanations and their outcomes are then evaluated for their distinctive strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be categorized in various ways: as primary sleep disorders, those associated with other mental disorders, or those linked to other issues. Primary sleep disorders encompass Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while sleep disorders tied to other mental disorders correlate with Axis I or Axis II disorders. Additional categories may stem from medical issues or substance use. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves difficulty in achieving or maintaining sleep, whereas Primary Hypersomnia pertains to challenges in staying awake, both persisting for at least a month. Narcolepsy includes symptoms like cataplexy and/or automatic REM. While Dyssomnias focus on initiating and maintaining sleep, Parasomnias involve behavioral or physiological irregularities during sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to other mental disorders involve sleep issues due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Intellectual Disabilities). This analysis centers on insomnia and somewhat on primary sleep disorders more broadly, in relation to the Biological and Sociocultural models.

The Biological model of sleep disorders highlights genetic, hereditary, and physiological aspects. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin play a crucial role in regulating sleep and wakefulness. Research involving mice discovered phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons crucial for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor triggers responses that facilitate sleep, and inhibiting it can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) was found to extend sleep duration (Matsuki et al., 2009). These findings suggest that animal studies with mice may be applicable to human studies. This indicates a genetic and environmental foundation for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A malfunction or absence of this receptor could hinder one's ability to achieve restful sleep without medication. From a sociocultural viewpoint, if the phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and any modification of the receptor might naturally disrupt an individual's sleep. This could adversely affect various life aspects such as education, career, and daily tasks requiring focus and repetition.

For roughly two and a half years, encompassing about four and a half semesters, I've been studying at University Park. Navigating the campus poses a challenge for many, including myself. During my freshman year, I was assigned to a dorm in East Halls, practically the easternmost boundary of the campus, aside from the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Making my way from Stuart Hall to classes located in distant buildings like Willard, near the campus core, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, particularly when the weather was unfavorable, which is often the case in State College. A conversation with a slightly older alum revealed that not too long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the main campus by vast stretches of unused land. Nowadays, that space is occupied by sports fields, massive new structures like the Creamery and the health services building, and is encircled by apartments. As the campus continues its growth, moving around becomes increasingly challenging. What could be the optimal solution for campus mobility? Bicycles are the answer. However, bikes alone won’t address the issue. Students need to ride them, and the infrastructure should accommodate cyclists’ needs.

A friend of mine recently returned to cycling after several years and expressed surprise at why he ever stopped. “Bikes are fantastic,” he remarked, “for a while, biking wasn’t considered cool, but it’s the best way to get around.” Besides being beneficial for health, cycling is also the most efficient form of travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some effort can take you over 30 miles. Like many students, I now reside off-campus, just as distant from the campus center as some dorms. Purchasing a bike has been my smartest decision this year. I have classes in the Thomas building daily, which is a good 25-minute walk from my home. With a bike, that journey can be reduced to 5 minutes if I pedal quickly. The only challenge is that Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas from my place, isn’t always an easy path, whether you're biking or walking. Walking has its merits, but I’m simply too busy for it. Without my bike, I’d have no other dependable way to reach my classes. Walking to Thomas every day would consume an additional 30-40 minutes, adding up to over two and a half hours weekly. Plus, the extra walking time to other classes and appointments would demand more time than I can afford.

In "Brave New World," Aldous Huxley critiques the looming dangers posed by technology and the capitalist system that underpins it, constructing a dystopian society to explore these themes. Within this society, individuals prioritize collective well-being over personal identity, being conditioned from birth to seek immediate pleasure as their ultimate goal. The citizens are mere instruments in a grand scheme, confined to a singular ideology orchestrated by the World Controller. Viewing the novel through the lens of Marxist theory reveals Huxley’s skepticism towards these developing systems. Marxist concepts such as homogeny and reification bolster the argument that Huxley's work critiques the flaws of the economic landscape emerging during his era.

Capitalism is ridiculed through the Marxist idea of false consciousness, wherein ordinary people remain unaware of their true economic relationships with other classes, focusing instead on personal gain. This stems from ideological control over the working class, vividly illustrated by the conditioning of the populace in "Brave New World." The lower social classes, like the Deltas and Gammas, lack genuine autonomy; through hypnopædia, they are driven to consume, spend, and indulge above all. This manipulation is overseen, as noted earlier, by the World Controller. Hegemony, the concept that certain social classes are entirely dominated by another group, is evident here. The lower classes are oblivious to this manipulation, literally embracing an ideology that sustains the existing structure—capitalism and consumerism. The upper classes have the awareness to recognize it but largely remain passive; few Alphas or Betas, aside from characters like Bernard, challenge their roles. The interactions among social classes significantly illustrate the perceived oppression within capitalism.

In "Brave New World," genuine relationships between individuals are absent. The novel intentionally blurs character distinctions, even among main characters, who lack depth. Huxley may be suggesting that the intertwining rise of technology and capitalism strips individuals of free will and self-expression. Love and intense emotions are nonexistent; instead, interactions are superficial, seen in the men’s comments about women focusing mainly on physical traits, like their "pneumatic quality," and in the women’s candid remarks about their experiences. Moreover, the satisfaction of each social class with their position in the hierarchy reflects capitalism's socioeconomic impact. Their unwavering conformity to their roles in the community echoes Marxist views on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their own superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and align with their peers.

Nearly four years ago, I enrolled in an Islam course at CBC, where one of the central debates was whether Islam could be considered a hostile religion. This question seems even more pertinent now than it did back then. Reflecting on the period since 9/11, I've noticed a shift in the media's portrayal of Islam, moving from a hostile stance against Islam and its extremists to an increased tolerance within American society. In 2001, it would have been hard to imagine a presidential candidate with a name like Barack Obama, who has a family background that includes Muslim ties.

The biography of the Prophet Muhammad fascinates me because, based on my understanding of his history, it seems to contradict his portrayed personality. Previously, I believed that Muhammad converted people to Islam by force, conquering tribes and compelling them to adopt the religion. However, the biography presents Muhammad as a misunderstood martyr who humbled himself, leading people to gradually recognize the 'truth' of his teachings and seek him out.

Interestingly, there are notable similarities between the ministries of Jesus and Muhammad's 'miracles.' One striking example is when Muhammad reportedly multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men. This style of narration suggests the authors wanted to depict Muhammad as a humble prophet, living in truth and performing miracles without needing to prove himself. This narrative bothers me because it seems to diminish the miracles and life of Jesus Christ, almost as if credit is being taken from Jesus and attributed to Muhammad.

The biography also contains numerous stories aimed at providing evidence of individuals 'independently' converting to Islam. However, these accounts often appear to rely on third-party perspectives, with the narrative indicating someone heard it from someone else, and so on. While the intention might be to offer proof of these stories' authenticity, I find this approach makes the accounts seem less credible and more suspicious.

What troubles me most about this work is the portrayal of Muhammad as a divine figure—humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. Yet, historical accounts challenge this depiction, and I wonder if today's Muslims are aware of the true history behind Muhammad’s ascent to power.

The teachings and beliefs that Jesus held during his lifetime quickly diverged from the path of Christian development that continued after his passing. Observing this historical progression, it becomes apparent that Christianity has gradually drifted from its origins. In today's world, there is an increasing awareness and a unique progressive trend. While some traditionalists persist and will resist any thought that extends beyond their teachings, this group may not have the influence to sway the majority. Within the Christian community, historical awareness is expected to grow significantly in the coming years. There will be a widespread desire to differentiate the doctrines that were incorporated into Christianity over time from the original intent of its founder. Though this process may take decades or even centuries, the eventual outcome seems inevitable: a significant shift back to Christianity’s original form. A growing movement will aim to peel away layers of doctrine, one by one, as if reversing the flow of time, until only the essence of what Jesus conveyed to humanity on behalf of God remains, untouched by subsequent interpretations. When this trend gains momentum in the United States and Europe, inspiring many to worship as if they were contemporaries of Jesus, adhering solely to his teachings, the church as an institution will remain robust to guide this transition. However, as theological perspectives revert, the vast diversity within Christianity will diminish, leading to more uniform beliefs and practices. Across regions and denominations, and bridging various divisions, we will observe a shift from differences to growing similarities. Human history is replete with significant reversions. A noteworthy example is the transformation of the Roman Empire from a persecutor of Christians to a Christian institution. Similarly, our nation has evolved from a history of African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The impending reversion will unfold within the realm of the Christian religion, retracing history to its origins and reducing diversity along the way. It is vital to recognize that this process will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally. So, what has transpired since Jesus' time? Looking back far enough, we find Judaism as the theological foundation for Christianity. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, the concept of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion. However, the Jewish population was not uniform; it was divided among Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common folk.

In my view, The Jungle vividly illustrates the inherent greed and self-interest present in human nature. Individuals tend to prioritize their own welfare and strive to enhance their lives without considering those less fortunate. This theme is prominently depicted in several ways throughout the novel. A clear example is seen in the actions of the factory owners and managers, who are solely focused on expanding their businesses to the greatest extent possible. They show little concern for the obstacles or the harm they cause in their pursuit of progress. Upton Sinclair's narrative captures this disregard through imagery like "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair aims to highlight the environmental destruction resulting from such industrial pollution, emphasizing the owners' indifference to the detrimental impact on people and animals. The toxic emissions from the factories and the waste runoff from numerous cattle pens in Packingtown exemplify this neglect.

Moreover, the employers exhibit a lack of empathy towards their workforce, who toil to generate wealth for them. In their relentless quest to maximize profits, they disregard the well-being of their employees: "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." Workers are subjected to grueling hours and face sudden layoffs without any severance or assistance in finding new employment. During the period depicted in The Jungle, few, if any, laws safeguarded workers' safety or welfare, allowing managers and owners to impose harsh working conditions and accelerate production. While the narrative does not explicitly state it, those laboring in Packingtown were expected to endure these dire circumstances both at work and at home. At the time, no organizations existed to provide support or guidance to the laborers. Although unions were established, they often exploited the workers rather than aiding them, exacerbating their plight. The workers, trapped in an oppressive system, were likened to slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

"Dream-Land" stands as one of Edgar Allan Poe’s own acclaimed poems. Within this work, Poe references “Thulé” in lines 6 and 56, a term that Mabbott links to Virgil, who mentioned it as an island located north of Britain, believed by the Greeks to be the world's boundary. Although Virgil indeed used the term, there exists a more contemporary source deserving recognition. Poe held a keen interest in German writers.

This reference is crucial as it highlights Poe's awareness of Goethe's literature. Karl J. Arndt, in his study "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," observes parallels between their poems, suggesting Poe might have been influenced by Goethe.

The "Oxford Companion to English Literature" describes Goethe as a celebrated poet and playwright, known for his poetic drama "Faust," released in two parts, first in 1808 and the second coinciding with Goethe's death in 1832. Within "Faust's" second part lies a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem narrates a king’s grief following his wife's death, symbolized by a goblet she gifted him. Consumed by sorrow, he drinks excessively, ultimately deciding to end his life. He bequeaths his possessions to his children, except the goblet, which he casts into the sea from a cliff before closing his eyes forever. The king’s portrayal in "The King of Thulé" bears a resemblance to the depiction in "Dream-Land," possibly reflecting Poe’s own struggles and reliance on alcohol. "Faust" was adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, a mere year before Poe incorporated "Thule" in “The Pit and the Pendulum.”

Poe refers to Thule on two occasions in his works. He mentions “ultima Thule” in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and uses it twice in “Dream-Land,” framing the poem. The two pieces, "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land," can be interpreted as companions. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes Thule’s landscape as dark and desolate, haunted by memories of deceased friends, and enveloped in a colorless shade. These elements resonate with Goethe’s “The King of Thule,” where the protagonist mourns his wife’s loss, feeling isolated and devoid of purpose to rule or live. The poem reads as if the speaker has entered into Goethe’s narrative.

Goethe was an influential figure, one Poe would likely have been familiar with, if only for his admiration of Tennyson. When asked about Tennyson, Poe spoke highly of him. Beyond the Tennyson connection, Poe would have encountered Goethe’s work through the numerous reproductions that followed its initial publication.

In the state of California, is it possible for a customer who was hurt after slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store to receive punitive damages by proving the store manager acted maliciously because he was twice informed of the spill but neglected to clean it for thirty minutes as he was having dinner? A judge might not immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s claim for punitive damages. To justify such a claim, the plaintiff must provide evidence that the defendant’s actions were carried out with a willful and conscious disregard for the likely harm resulting from those actions, and that the behavior was despicable. Palmer could argue that Martin should have been aware of the likely harm from ignoring the spill, as multiple D&D customers had been injured in similar incidents in the months before Palmer's mishap; yet despite this awareness, he did not ensure the spill was addressed. Although Palmer’s assertion that Martin's actions were despicable is less compelling, it still holds weight given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009, and Martin did not take adequate measures to ensure the store's safety.

On October 13, 2009, around 5:00 pm, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in one of the aisles. Martin replied that he was on his dinner break and didn’t have time for customer complaints. At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also informed Martin about the spill, to which he responded in the same manner. At 5:30 pm on that day, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and suffered a severe back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five other slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is now pursuing compensatory and punitive damages for her injury, and the decision on whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim is under consideration.

In California, punitive damages may be recovered for a breach of an obligation not stemming from a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice" according to Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). Malice is defined by the statute as conduct intended to cause harm, or in the absence of intent, behavior that is "despicable" and carried out with "a willful and conscious disregard for the rights or safety of others," as stated in § (c)(1). Courts have described actions as malicious when done with conscious disregard for the plaintiff's rights if the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct and willfully and deliberately failed to avert those consequences," as noted in Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Ever since she could remember, there was always an emptiness within her, a longing that seemed insatiable. This feeling began to manifest when she was around 14, just stepping into the world of adolescence. Three years later, at 17, the feeling persisted. By then, she realized she was yearning for someone, not something. Despite this realization, no boys sparked her interest. Some boys had shown interest in her, trying awkwardly to win over someone who seemed unattainable, but none captured her attention. She frequently pondered this unusual predicament, questioning why a teenage girl like her would feel this way. Years of reflection yielded various theories, but none she found convincing enough to dwell on. Thus, she continued her life, persistently questioning her desires.

Days at home were usually serene. Her parents were gentle and composed individuals. They rarely argued with each other and seldom with their daughter. Their only disputes revolved around her asserting her independence and vibrant personality. Despite being the child of such tranquil parents, she contrasted their calm demeanor with her lively and engaging nature, which made her quite likable, complemented by her kind-heartedness.

Today, however, was anything but calm. As she moved from one room to another, seeking new inspiration, a sudden scream echoed from the kitchen, her mother's lovely voice. Panic-stricken, she dashed to the kitchen, her heart racing as she asked anxiously, "Mom?! Mom, what's happening?!" There she found her mother on the floor, clearly in distress, repeatedly whispering "Ow" in short, labored breaths. She rushed to her mother's side, placing a reassuring hand on her. "Ouch ... sweetie, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." Her mother's words were hurried and strained, and it was clear she was in severe pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me how I can help you." Guided by her mother, she was grateful for the strength she had gained from her physical training. She carefully carried her mother to the car, laid her down in the backseat, and drove off.

The hospital was filled with the scent of disinfectant and an air of anxiety. But she hardly noticed, her mind solely focused on her mother's well-being. She swiftly brought her mother inside, calling out for medical assistance. Concerned faces gathered, and someone quickly brought a gurney to lay her mother on. They promptly took her for examination, leaving her daughter to anxiously wait.

Her mother had toppled from a step stool while attempting to retrieve a vase from the highest shelf in their cabinet.

This research aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a decreased risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and mortality due to stroke. The aMed diet is an adaptation of the Med diet and is marked by increased consumption of plant-based foods, such as plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (in place of saturated fats), and fish, while reducing the intake of animal products and saturated fats. The diet also permits moderate alcohol consumption.

Previous prospective studies have shown a negative correlation between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of overall and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. An intervention trial revealed that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. However, prior studies did not specifically concentrate on stroke or stroke mortality.

In this epidemiological study, 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63 years, without a history of CVD or diabetes, were monitored as part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the researchers calculated an aMed diet score six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to evaluate nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of the nurses remained involved throughout the 20-year span. The FFQs underwent validation studies. Instances of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through examination of medical or hospital records, autopsy reports, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, these were considered "probable" and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions classified as such. For each FFQ, calculations were made for body mass index, smoking status, use of aspirin, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use. Starting in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was also assessed.

To minimize random variation for individuals and more accurately reflect long-term dietary consumption, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated by averaging scores from the two preceding years. Adjustments for "confounders" (factors that might skew results) were made by considering age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

The study employed Cox proportional-hazard modeling to evaluate the relationship between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke categories.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as shown by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a reduced risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up period, there were 2,391 incident cases of CHD, 1,763 incident cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combining fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the highest aMed quintile exhibited a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile, with a relative risk (RR) of 0.71.

A sign declares that Hitler is alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, known for her role in Juno, stands alone at a street corner holding a cardboard sign with this unsettling message written in Sharpie. Burma, also called Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation ruled by a harsh military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, the country witnessed a series of street protests, the first in a decade. These demonstrations, led by numerous Burmese monks, were dubbed "The Saffron Revolution" after the color of the monks' robes. Initially, the Burmese government tolerated these peaceful gatherings, but as public interest grew, the situation deteriorated into a violent conflict between the monks and the military junta. The military began raiding monasteries across the nation. Foreign journalists were arrested on the spot, and a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, merely for covering a protest. Official reports claim 13 deaths, but Colonel Hla Win, who recently defected, suggested that fatalities were in the thousands.

Such events are not unprecedented. Governments have long sought to suppress dissent to maintain absolute control over their people. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine selection to justify their authority over all societal aspects. Japanese emperors were viewed as deities, meant to guide their people to success. Meanwhile, then U.S. President George W. Bush reportedly held regular calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, linked to the Republic Party.

Some notorious examples include the Tiananmen Square protests of June 4, 1989, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students rallied against the government's authoritarianism. Death toll estimates from these protests vary widely, from 200-300 according to official Chinese reports to 2,000-3,000 as per the Chinese Red Cross. The Rwandan genocide in the 1990s saw Hutu militias, supported by the government, systematically exterminating Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of ethnicity. Hitler's 'Third Reich' is another extreme case, where Jews were systematically persecuted and killed across multiple countries.

Duke Ellington's enduring influence in jazz can be largely attributed to his extensive career and his exceptional skill in shaping his orchestra's sound. While his piano contributions are often understated in many of the pieces considered for this assignment, Ellington's brilliance as a composer shines through in his ability to craft intricate and layered compositions that highlighted the unique talents of his band members. He created a structure that allowed soloists the freedom to improvise, while also composing tightly orchestrated pieces that leveraged the distinctive styles of his musicians to bring musical concepts to life. This approach not only spotlighted individual musicians but also enhanced the overall tone of the orchestra, resulting in cohesive and inventive soundscapes tailored to each composition. Ellington's adeptness at understanding both individual and collective sound within his ensemble enabled him to produce some of the most groundbreaking works in jazz history.

In its discussion of Ellington's sound and innovative approach, the Grove Music dictionary cites "Creole Love Call" as an example of his use of the voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This piece illustrates Ellington's technique of using voice to add depth and color, unencumbered by lyrics. "Creole Love Call" also showcases Ellington's knack for complementing the style of his soloists, a skill evident throughout his career. As a slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece, it unfolds over six choruses:

Chorus 1: Engages in a call and response between voice and reeds, starting smooth and melodic, then shifting to a coarser tone by the end.
Chorus 2: Features a muted trumpet solo that expands on the main melody, highlighting several elongated blue notes.
Chorus 3: Presents a sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, supported by a subtly syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The entire band echoes the first chorus with call and response from the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: Acts as the climactic point, with reeds initiating a high-register call and response, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: Returns to the structure of the first chorus, with voice and reeds engaging in call and response. Here, the voice employs the "growl" technique, functioning as an instrumental solo.
Tag: Concludes with a brief vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending from a trombone.

Ellington's use of the voice to add tonal dimension to this piece exemplifies a hallmark of his style. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington marries his gift for precise orchestration with his sensitivity to tonal color. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing blends the vocal quality of Miley's trumpet with Cox's instrumental-like voice to create a rich, complementary sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" further develops these concepts, with Ellington employing Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a fixture in his orchestra, to great effect as he introduces the melody on a muted trombone.

What drives the evolutionary paths of organisms? Are there limitations or constraints that steer the course of evolutionary transformations? Back in 1917, D’Arcy Thompson remarked that “Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms,” and this observation still holds true today. In more recent times, researchers have applied mathematical modeling to study the general patterns of mollusk skeletogenesis through both their development and evolutionary history (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research focuses on how mathematical modeling of changes during the development and evolutionary history of Prunum, along with experimental studies, can illuminate the processes that determine the direction and scale of evolutionary-developmental changes. We utilized X-ray images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters that could be employed to simulate both theoretical and real skeletal structures. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We created models of theoretical shell forms to explore the limits of potential morphological changes in Prunum. These findings are being integrated with experimental and descriptive research to gain a deeper understanding of major evolutionary events within this group.

A shell can be imagined as a structure that moves through a 360-degree space over time. These rotations or turns of a coiled shell are known as whorls, which are envisioned as spiraling around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the core of the shell and is termed the columella. The rate at which the whorls expand can differ, and each whorl is separated by a continuous line called a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the final one, known as the body whorl. The spire consists of all whorls except the last one. The tip of the spire is the apex, and the opposite end is the base. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be observed from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. (The “standard” orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the observer and the apex directed upward.)

The method for counting whorls is outlined below. First, the shell is viewed from the apical perspective to determine where the initial suture starts. A line can then be drawn to divide the shell into two sections. Whorls are counted starting from this line and are measured to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a sequence of apertures that progress through time and space as the animal constructs its shell. It is feasible to trace the path of the aperture using the coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radii of the aperture.

This trajectory can be depicted both graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical model is established, it becomes possible to adjust parameters and alter the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

Over the past decade, Indonesia has experienced little change in its neonatal and infant mortality rates. Although the nation is progressing well towards achieving several Millennium Development Goals, including those related to water and sanitation, the advancements in child and maternal health remain insufficient to reach the 2015 targets. The underlying reasons for these gaps will be explored below, highlighting the necessity of enhancing the health system over isolated programmatic solutions.

Indonesia has seen an increase in births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now falling into this category. However, this figure includes traditional practitioners like midwives, who may lack the ability to handle complicated pregnancies (which contributes to the high incidence of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). Thus, the apparent progress in this area is somewhat misleading, and significant improvements are still needed. Additionally, there has been a reduction in the percentage of children under five with diarrhea receiving treatment from a health professional. Although data on postnatal care is not comprehensive, it is evident that this remains a critical issue, with low service rates nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates remain unexpectedly low at around 4%. This statistic also highlights a concerning issue of disparity. While the c-section rate is 7% in urban areas, it drops to merely 2% in rural regions, indicating unequal healthcare access across the country. Access issues are also evident in terms of vertical equity, with a 27% difference in service utilization between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles. The poorer segments of society face greater challenges in accessing healthcare, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

As we consider steps to enhance neonatal and maternal care indicators, a fundamental question arises: how can service deficiencies be most effectively tackled? Specifically, should Indonesia focus on developing targeted program-specific strategies or work towards reinforcing the overall health system without concentrating solely on maternal and child care before and after pregnancy? While programmatic solutions for the outlined issues are appealing due to their focused and manageable goals, which typically yield quicker results, there are potential drawbacks. A significant downside is that prioritizing a specific health sector can lead to diminished funding for others, drawing human resources away (a scenario seen with the impact of international HIV/AIDS funding on the family planning sector). Moreover, operating several parallel programs for a single area can result in service duplication and lack of coordination, increasing paperwork and supply requisition challenges.

Over the last century, the categorization of popular music has evolved to include an overwhelming number of genres, making it challenging to enumerate them all comprehensively. Adding to the complexity, nearly every genre—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, among others—has given rise to numerous sub-genres and further subdivisions. Notably, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has emerged as one of the most varied and expressive forms of popular music over the past four decades. Its expressiveness lies in its ability to convey a broad spectrum of emotions, typically leaning towards the darker end. Its diversity became apparent shortly after the genre emerged, as enthusiasts recognized its adaptability and began experimenting to create new sub-genres, leading to further sub-sub-genres, a trend that persists to this day.

At present, the heavy metal movement has reached a stage where the abundance of niche groups makes defining heavy metal itself a challenge. Despite incorporating numerous elements from other genres, heavy metal, like all music, has its origins. To truly grasp the essence of today's metal music, one must first comprehend the metal movement and why it is perceived as a movement rather than merely a genre.

In many respects, metal represents a movement characterized by darkness. It can be seen as a "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more aggression, more theatricality. With less primitivism and more technical prowess, musicians in metal bands demonstrate notable instrumental skill, evident in their music. Metal is also, perhaps unsurprisingly, a movement heavily influenced by drug culture. The psychedelic drug wave of the mid-1970s led people to experiment with wild, otherworldly records, using drugs as a creative catalyst. It embodies many dark, visceral elements, a stark contrast to the lighter qualities prevalent in much of popular music. Furthermore, later metal generations have drawn inspiration from the dark, intense characteristics prevalent in the Romantic Era, with lyrics that reflect the movement's inherent darkness.

An example is found in the lyrics of "Helter Skelter," which reveal the darker side of the Beatles. The song portrays an erratic journey, often interpreted as drug-induced. Considered by some as one of the inaugural Heavy Metal songs, it was a reaction to a Rolling Stones track with a similarly heavy, dark tone. The Beatles aimed to demonstrate their capacity to match the Stones' intensity, leading them to include this song on The White Album.

Some years prior to the emergence of Surrealist painters and their dream-inspired creations, Henri Rousseau was meticulously crafting his own visions, both in reality and imagination. His 1910 masterpiece, The Dream, not only depicts a woman marveling at the enchanting landscape of her dream, but also encapsulates Rousseau’s personal aspirations and challenges as an artist. From the onset of his artistic journey, Rousseau yearned for recognition, acceptance, and admiration from his peers and art enthusiasts. This pursuit led to a profound internal conflict: should he imitate prevalent artistic styles to gain acceptance within the critical art community he cherished, or should he chart his own course, embracing a unique creative expression? 

To appreciate The Dream through this lens, it is essential to understand Rousseau’s life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, France, Rousseau was the son of a tinsmith and hardware merchant who enjoyed a modest lifestyle (Shattuck 47). Lacking formal artistic education, Rousseau worked as a gabelou, a municipal toll service employee, until the age of forty, despite being mistakenly referred to as a customs inspector or douanier (Shattuck 46). After the tragic loss of his first wife, Clémence, and eight of their children, leaving him with only one surviving daughter, Julia, Rousseau sought solace in painting, hoping it would provide comfort and a fresh start (Shattuck 49). Unlike his contemporaries who romanticized rural life, Rousseau remained a folk painter, reflecting the ambitions and dreams typical of his social class.

Rousseau’s preoccupation with gaining acceptance in the art world is understandable when considering his background: he was self-taught, started his artistic career later in life, and was creating alongside many renowned modern artists. Despite years of dedication, Rousseau only began receiving recognition around the same time as Matisse, who was establishing his artistic reputation. In Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon notes that while Rousseau and Matisse were artistic rivals, they differed in their approach and motivation: “Matisse feared painting in a clichéd manner, whereas Rousseau longed to create art so conventional it would secure him a place with the Artiste Français” (92).

Numerous intellectuals have speculated about the deep link between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I think there's a fundamental reason for this connection. John Keats, in his poem "Ode on a Grecian Urn," famously states, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we understand in life comes through education or personal experience. Yet, as Keats suggests, we seem to grasp ethics and aesthetics without needing explicit teaching. Both fields aim more to describe than to prescribe. Our exploration of morality and beauty primarily seeks to explain why an artwork or piece of literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, instead of laying out rules for determining or creating good art or ethical behavior.

Critiques of art or morals often fall short of capturing the true essence of what makes something good or beautiful. Discussions about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for instance, might focus on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but these don't fully explain why it is considered great art. When people are asked about their favorite artwork or literature, they often start with something like, "There's just something about it," before offering a more detailed or critical analysis. I believe both art and morals cannot be wholly reduced to descriptions of their attributes. As Flannery O'Connor notes, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how thoroughly we describe a piece of literature, there's something beyond that remains. I think ethics shares this feature. Wittgenstein remarks, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental.” I propose that this "something," this indescribable quality, is the most powerful aspect of art and morality, and it's this transcendental characteristic that links ethics and aesthetics.

I believe morality and art are closely related because we experience both at a profound, almost ineffable level. They touch us in ways that can be felt but not fully articulated. This connection is even more pronounced in the realm of literature. As McKean comments, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Modern Germany is recognized as a powerful and unified nation, showcasing a diverse tapestry of culture that stretches from the Alpine shadows in Munich to the coastal city of Kiel on the Baltic Sea. This cultural richness is evident from Cologne on the Rhine River, through Germany's heartland, reaching the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. It is unsurprising that contemporary Germany is a product of various origins and tribes, given its unique cultural heritage.

The land historically known as Germania is the ancestral home of the Germans, though the origins of its name are debated among academics. Tacitus suggested that it originated from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, who were previously known as Germans before crossing the Rhine to fight the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first mentioned the term "Germanus" in his writings on the Gallic Wars, where he described conflicts with Germanic tribes that frequently crossed the Rhine with questionable intentions. He borrowed this term from the Gauls to differentiate between the conquered Gauls and the unconquered Germanic tribes. Some scholars speculate that the name may refer to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In his commentary on the wars, Caesar noted, “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC). Other theories suggest the name might derive from the weapon they used, a spear known as a "ger" (O.E.D, 2010), or from the Old Irish word "garim," meaning "to shout," reflecting the Germans' boisterous nature (Names of Germany).

In his work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," written in AD 98, the Roman historian Tacitus described the origins of the Germans: “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98).

Why would anyone abandon Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not at that time. They occasionally launched campaigns into Germania for resources but generally returned to their vast empire. As Germanic tribes emerged in the first century, they settled at the edges of the Roman Empire, trading goods and offering their skills as soldiers within the Roman army (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

In Shakespeare's Twelfth Night, the theme of disguise plays a critical role, suggesting that while it can effectively sustain deception for extended periods, ultimately, individuals must abandon these false identities to avoid losing their true selves. A significant challenge in ending such a deception is the potential alienation that may follow. Therefore, one faces a choice between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others. Some might respond indifferently to being deceived, while others may feel deeply offended by the ruse.

The issue of deception is particularly complex when it involves gender role reversal, raising questions such as why someone would feel compelled to abandon their identity and assume the guise of the opposite gender. In Viola's situation, her disguise serves as a protective measure: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). Newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola adopts a male persona to safeguard herself against potential threats. Her strategy succeeds, but it also distances her from the women who could have supported her. Complicating matters further, Olivia, mistaking Viola for Sebastian, falls in love with her: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Additionally, Viola must navigate her own romantic feelings for Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261).

To contemporary readers, Twelfth Night might be viewed as a narrative exploring how deception can reveal hidden emotions, especially for characters like Olivia and Orsino. Certain parts of the play suggest that these characters confront subconscious feelings prompted by Viola/Cesario's presence. For instance, Olivia's attraction to Cesario raises the question of whether she is drawn to the perceived masculinity or if she harbors latent feelings for women. However, it is more plausible that Shakespeare intended Olivia to satirize those of his era who judge others based solely on appearances. This is supported by how easily Olivia transfers her affections to Sebastian and starts viewing Cesario/Viola as a sibling rather than a romantic interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

Observers have often highlighted the harshness of German colonial rule, particularly regarding the atrocities committed against the Ovaherero and Nama peoples in what was then German South West Africa. While such a generalization cannot fully capture the complexity of an entire colonial empire, it is important to recognize that the German colonial territories differed widely in terms of policies and governance styles, reflecting their geographic diversity. Similarly, educational initiatives varied across the colonies. When the British assumed control of German East Africa (present-day Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a considerable number of educated and literate Africans. German efforts in education in places like Kamerun and other colonies were acknowledged positively by contemporary writers.

The circumstances in South West Africa (now Namibia) were markedly different. Unlike East Africa, where the government was proactive in establishing state schools and significantly involved in the education of the local population, in South West Africa, educational responsibilities for the native inhabitants were largely handed over to missionary societies with minimal government assistance. Conversely, substantial resources were allocated to the education of Europeans in the colony, with the establishment of state schools and increased support and regulation of missionary schools. These educational policies had lasting impacts on South West Africa, persisting beyond the period of German rule. While other German colonies had notable numbers of educated and literate Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to this distinct experience in South West Africa. This paper aims to delve deeper into these factors, focusing on recent research concerning the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There is an abundance of literature specifically addressing education within the German colonial empire. Most of these works are in German, written during or shortly after the period of German colonial dominance. Early writings primarily sought to outline the characteristics of educational systems in these territories. Subsequent English-language studies expanded the analysis through comparative examinations of education across different German colonies and more in-depth evaluations of specific educational elements. These studies highlighted notable disparities in educational systems among various colonies. The most significant work addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen’s analysis of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen contrasts the educational systems of the two colonies and explores the factors that led to their differences. According to Cohen, the substantial settler population in South West Africa accounts for many distinctive features of the colony’s educational system.

Relative to Germany’s other colonial territories, South West Africa had a somewhat temperate climate, though much of the land is arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these relatively favorable living conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 Europeans resided in South West Africa, whereas the next largest settler population was in East Africa, with only 5,336 Europeans.

The United States and Mexico serve as an illustration of two countries that once experienced a prolonged rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848 marked the peak of this conflict, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, acquiring Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts occurred between these nations, finally subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry originated from clashes between Americans and Mexicans over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, along with significant material interests (Schmitt 1974, pp. 30-31). 

This scenario is similar to many other countries that maintain an enduring rivalry with a neighboring nation. Countries sharing borders often encounter conflicting interests, leading to rival positions. The United States and Mexico are comparable to other long-standing rivalries between nations with shared borders. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both nations are geographically close to the United States and have historically been rivals, while other Latin American countries have generally enjoyed amicable relations with the U.S.

Religious differences created a division between the United States and Mexico, a challenge that has affected many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) mentions that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). Unlike the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which was partly an ideological struggle and partly a competition over crucial interests, the U.S.-Mexico ideological tensions were rooted in religious preferences. This mistrust stemmed from the historical distrust between the English and Spanish, and these inherited feelings posed a significant hurdle in establishing friendly foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) identify 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes, as described by Diehl and Goerts, involved territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier challenges. Raids by bandits and outlaws on American border towns were a persistent problem until both nations exerted military control over their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97). Schmitt (1974) points out that the rivalry began to diminish as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109), eventually concluding as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century (p. 110).

Fifteen years ago, an unforeseen illness left me suddenly disabled, a condition I had never encountered before.

At that time, I was working as a nurse. I had chosen this career path driven by a profound need for the stability and security that I lacked during my childhood. "Nursing will always provide job opportunities; people will always need healthcare," was the advice I repeatedly heard as I grew up. Although my true aspirations were to become a scientist or a journalist—or ideally a blend of both—I opted for nursing.

However, at 46, I found myself single, with no financial savings to rely on, and unable to work. Even now, after 15 years of depending on Social Security Disability, I have very little that I can call my own. Every day remains a challenge, continuously undermining my sense of security, safety, and self-worth. Uncertainty defines my life, yet one thing remains clear: I couldn't have survived all these years without the support of my family and a few close friends, regardless of my inner strength. When true disaster hits, any sense of strength quickly diminishes.

The reality is that life is filled with both major and minor emergencies. No amount of preparation can guarantee a smooth path; some challenges are simply too immense to tackle alone.

I fully agree that we in the U.S. should not rely solely on the government, whose systems are deteriorating. I would prefer to see Americans rediscovering trust in each other—learning to offer and accept help—rather than each of us building isolated defenses.

Conservative rhetoric often praises "rugged individualism" as a cornerstone of American history. However, the truth is that our ancestors endured hardships through compassion, mutual respect, and resource sharing. Pioneers who ventured across the Rockies in wagon trains didn't succeed by going it alone.

Therefore, while it’s important to be prepared—I am, with a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting, duct tape, flashlights, batteries, candles, waterproof matches, and canned food—it's equally crucial to connect with your neighbors.

If you have the means to cultivate a small farm or preserve your own food, it's a wise choice. A wood stove is also advantageous, provided you don’t live in an apartment.

Yet, as you take these steps, make an effort to get to know those around you.

In the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince, later known as Buddha, was born. Throughout his lifetime, he chose to leave worldly life behind and reached enlightenment, which gave rise to Buddhism. The most traditional branch of this religion is Theravada Buddhism. With a history spanning about 2,500 years, Buddhism has evolved and looks quite distinct from what it was during Buddha’s time. This evolution is evident, for example, in Sri Lanka—a Theravada Buddhist country—where an annual water-cutting ceremony is held. This event involves both monks and laypeople and holds religious significance, even though Buddha did not mention such festivities. These changes range from surface-level traditions to the deep soteriological essence of the faith. Over time, the Theravada Buddhist community, including both monks and lay followers, has adapted its doctrinal principles due to various influences, both from within and outside the community, and both positive and negative.

Several key terms will be used frequently in this discussion. The distinction between internal and external forces is crucial. Internal forces are those arising from members within the Buddhasasana, regardless of their monastic status, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces aim to harm or disrupt the Buddhist community, stemming from negative views of Buddhism. Benign forces, on the other hand, do not intend to harm or help the community, though their impact may inadvertently be beneficial or detrimental. These concepts will be referenced throughout the discussion.

To start with, it is essential to explore the fundamental doctrines at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma consists of the Tripitaka, or the three baskets, of Buddhist scripture. The Sutta Pitaka includes the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. These metaphysical ideas include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (the inherent suffering of life), and Anicca (the impermanence of all things). Understanding these concepts is essential to ending Sansara, the perpetual cycle of death and rebirth. Upon enlightenment, Sansara ceases, along with lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka provides rules for living. Laypeople adhere to five precepts: not to kill, lie, steal, engage in sexual misconduct, or consume intoxicants. Monks follow many more strict rules. The four noble truths are central to Buddhism: first, the truth of Dukkha, that life is suffering; second, that attachment causes suffering; and third, that suffering can be overcome.
