Early writings primarily sought to outline the characteristics of educational systems in these territories. Subsequent English-language studies expanded the analysis through comparative examinations of education across different German colonies and more in-depth evaluations of specific educational elements. These studies highlighted notable disparities in educational systems among various colonies. The most significant work addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen’s analysis of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen contrasts the educational systems of the two colonies and explores the factors that led to their differences. According to Cohen, the substantial settler population in South West Africa accounts for many distinctive features of the colony’s educational system.

Relative to Germany’s other colonial territories, South West Africa had a somewhat temperate climate, though much of the land is arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these relatively favorable living conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 Europeans resided in South West Africa, whereas the next largest settler population was in East Africa, with only 5,336 Europeans.

The United States and Mexico serve as an illustration of two countries that once experienced a prolonged rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848 marked the peak of this conflict, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, acquiring Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts occurred between these nations, finally subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry originated from clashes between Americans and Mexicans over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, along with significant material interests (Schmitt 1974, pp. 30-31). 

This scenario is similar to many other countries that maintain an enduring rivalry with a neighboring nation. Countries sharing borders often encounter conflicting interests, leading to rival positions. The United States and Mexico are comparable to other long-standing rivalries between nations with shared borders. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both nations are geographically close to the United States and have historically been rivals, while other Latin American countries have generally enjoyed amicable relations with the U.S.

Religious differences created a division between the United States and Mexico, a challenge that has affected many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) mentions that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). Unlike the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which was partly an ideological struggle and partly a competition over crucial interests, the U.S.-Mexico ideological tensions were rooted in religious preferences. This mistrust stemmed from the historical distrust between the English and Spanish, and these inherited feelings posed a significant hurdle in establishing friendly foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) identify 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes, as described by Diehl and Goerts, involved territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier challenges. Raids by bandits and outlaws on American border towns were a persistent problem until both nations exerted military control over their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97). Schmitt (1974) points out that the rivalry began to diminish as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109), eventually concluding as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century (p. 110).

Fifteen years ago, an unforeseen illness left me suddenly disabled, a condition I had never encountered before.

At that time, I was working as a nurse. I had chosen this career path driven by a profound need for the stability and security that I lacked during my childhood. "Nursing will always provide job opportunities; people will always need healthcare," was the advice I repeatedly heard as I grew up. Although my true aspirations were to become a scientist or a journalist—or ideally a blend of both—I opted for nursing.

However, at 46, I found myself single, with no financial savings to rely on, and unable to work. Even now, after 15 years of depending on Social Security Disability, I have very little that I can call my own. Every day remains a challenge, continuously undermining my sense of security, safety, and self-worth. Uncertainty defines my life, yet one thing remains clear: I couldn't have survived all these years without the support of my family and a few close friends, regardless of my inner strength. When true disaster hits, any sense of strength quickly diminishes.

The reality is that life is filled with both major and minor emergencies. No amount of preparation can guarantee a smooth path; some challenges are simply too immense to tackle alone.

I fully agree that we in the U.S. should not rely solely on the government, whose systems are deteriorating. I would prefer to see Americans rediscovering trust in each other—learning to offer and accept help—rather than each of us building isolated defenses.

Conservative rhetoric often praises "rugged individualism" as a cornerstone of American history. However, the truth is that our ancestors endured hardships through compassion, mutual respect, and resource sharing. Pioneers who ventured across the Rockies in wagon trains didn't succeed by going it alone.

Therefore, while it’s important to be prepared—I am, with a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting, duct tape, flashlights, batteries, candles, waterproof matches, and canned food—it's equally crucial to connect with your neighbors.

If you have the means to cultivate a small farm or preserve your own food, it's a wise choice. A wood stove is also advantageous, provided you don’t live in an apartment.

Yet, as you take these steps, make an effort to get to know those around you.

In the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince, later known as Buddha, was born. Throughout his lifetime, he chose to leave worldly life behind and reached enlightenment, which gave rise to Buddhism. The most traditional branch of this religion is Theravada Buddhism. With a history spanning about 2,500 years, Buddhism has evolved and looks quite distinct from what it was during Buddha’s time. This evolution is evident, for example, in Sri Lanka—a Theravada Buddhist country—where an annual water-cutting ceremony is held. This event involves both monks and laypeople and holds religious significance, even though Buddha did not mention such festivities. These changes range from surface-level traditions to the deep soteriological essence of the faith. Over time, the Theravada Buddhist community, including both monks and lay followers, has adapted its doctrinal principles due to various influences, both from within and outside the community, and both positive and negative.

Several key terms will be used frequently in this discussion. The distinction between internal and external forces is crucial. Internal forces are those arising from members within the Buddhasasana, regardless of their monastic status, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces aim to harm or disrupt the Buddhist community, stemming from negative views of Buddhism. Benign forces, on the other hand, do not intend to harm or help the community, though their impact may inadvertently be beneficial or detrimental. These concepts will be referenced throughout the discussion.

To start with, it is essential to explore the fundamental doctrines at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma consists of the Tripitaka, or the three baskets, of Buddhist scripture. The Sutta Pitaka includes the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. These metaphysical ideas include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (the inherent suffering of life), and Anicca (the impermanence of all things). Understanding these concepts is essential to ending Sansara, the perpetual cycle of death and rebirth. Upon enlightenment, Sansara ceases, along with lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka provides rules for living. Laypeople adhere to five precepts: not to kill, lie, steal, engage in sexual misconduct, or consume intoxicants. Monks follow many more strict rules. The four noble truths are central to Buddhism: first, the truth of Dukkha, that life is suffering; second, that attachment causes suffering; and third, that suffering can be overcome.
